1
00:02:27,300 --> 00:02:29,097
Tutti-frutti.

2
00:02:29,269 --> 00:02:32,761
Most generous gift
from American sergeant.

3
00:02:32,939 --> 00:02:37,967
Lovely ladies, kind gentlemen,
pleased to introduce myself.

4
00:02:38,345 --> 00:02:42,304
Sakini by name,
interpreter by profession.

5
00:02:42,482 --> 00:02:45,610
Education by the ancient dictionary.

6
00:02:45,785 --> 00:02:50,722
Okinawan by whim of gods.

7
00:02:51,725 --> 00:02:56,662
History of Okinawa reveal
distinguished record of conquerors.

8
00:02:56,830 --> 00:03:03,065
We have honor to be subjugated
in 14th century by Chinese pirates.

9
00:03:03,236 --> 00:03:06,069
In 16th century, by English missionary.

10
00:03:06,239 --> 00:03:09,174
In 18th century, by Japanese warlords.

11
00:03:09,342 --> 00:03:13,403
And in 20th century,
by American Marine.

12
00:03:13,580 --> 00:03:15,878
Okinawa very fortunate.

13
00:03:16,049 --> 00:03:20,383
Culture brought to us.
Not have to leave home for it.

14
00:03:20,553 --> 00:03:23,613
And we learn many thing.

15
00:03:23,790 --> 00:03:29,251
Most important, that rest of world
not like Okinawa.

16
00:03:29,429 --> 00:03:34,264
World filled with delightful variation.
Example:

17
00:03:34,434 --> 00:03:37,665
In Okinawa, no locks on doors.

18
00:03:37,837 --> 00:03:40,601
Bad manners not to trust neighbors.

19
00:03:40,774 --> 00:03:44,676
In America, lock and key big industry.

20
00:03:44,844 --> 00:03:49,611
Conclusion: Bad manners, good business.

21
00:03:50,683 --> 00:03:52,742
Another example:

22
00:03:52,919 --> 00:03:58,118
In Okinawa, wash self in public bath
with nude lady quite proper...

23
00:03:58,291 --> 00:04:02,318
...but a picture of nude lady
in private home quite improper.

24
00:04:02,495 --> 00:04:07,125
In America, statue of nude lady in park
win prize...

25
00:04:07,300 --> 00:04:12,795
...but nude lady in flesh in park
win a penalty.

26
00:04:12,972 --> 00:04:14,496
Conclusion:

27
00:04:14,674 --> 00:04:19,134
Pornography, question of geography.

28
00:04:20,113 --> 00:04:24,311
But Okinawa most eager
to be educated by conquerors.

29
00:04:24,484 --> 00:04:26,952
Not easy to learn.

30
00:04:27,120 --> 00:04:30,578
Sometimes very painful.

31
00:04:30,757 --> 00:04:33,885
But pain make man think.

32
00:04:34,327 --> 00:04:37,319
Thought make man wise.

33
00:04:37,497 --> 00:04:41,092
And wisdom make life endurable.

34
00:04:41,835 --> 00:04:44,633
So now...

35
00:04:44,804 --> 00:04:50,037
Now we going to tell you little story
to demonstrate splendid example...

36
00:04:50,210 --> 00:04:54,943
...of benevolent assimilation of democracy
by Okinawa.

37
00:04:56,149 --> 00:04:58,174
Boss by name of Colonel Purdy III.

38
00:04:59,752 --> 00:05:04,553
Number three after name indicate
he is son of a son of a son.

39
00:05:04,958 --> 00:05:06,619
Colonel Purdy put up many sign.

40
00:05:08,194 --> 00:05:10,355
This exceedingly civilized.

41
00:05:10,530 --> 00:05:14,864
Make it very easy for uncivilized
to know what not to do.

42
00:05:15,034 --> 00:05:17,798
Here laundry of officer...

43
00:05:17,971 --> 00:05:21,668
...not to fraternize with laundry
of enlisted man.

44
00:05:28,348 --> 00:05:31,408
This gentleman,
honorable Sergeant Gregovich...

45
00:05:31,584 --> 00:05:37,079
...assistant to Colonel Purdy,
but not a son of a son of son.

46
00:05:38,291 --> 00:05:41,556
You know what he's doing? Explanation:

47
00:05:41,728 --> 00:05:45,289
Colonel Purdy great student of history.

48
00:05:45,465 --> 00:05:47,899
So every month, wife of Colonel Purdy...

49
00:05:48,067 --> 00:05:50,763
<i>...send him magazine
called Adventure Magazine.</i>

50
00:05:50,937 --> 00:05:54,634
Cover have picture of pirate
with a black patch over eye.

51
00:05:54,807 --> 00:05:57,241
Everyone try to steal magazine.

52
00:05:57,410 --> 00:06:00,208
So colonel hide under desk
so he can read first...

53
00:06:00,380 --> 00:06:02,905
...but the sergeant always find.

54
00:06:14,594 --> 00:06:17,085
He's a smart mouse.

55
00:06:24,103 --> 00:06:28,540
This gentleman,
exalted boss Colonel Purdy III.

56
00:06:28,708 --> 00:06:30,903
Colonel very wise man.

57
00:06:31,077 --> 00:06:35,309
Every morning look up at the sky
and make a prophecy.

58
00:06:36,282 --> 00:06:38,409
It's not gonna rain today.

59
00:06:38,585 --> 00:06:42,248
And you know what? Not... Not rain.

60
00:06:42,422 --> 00:06:47,951
Of course it not rain this time of year
in whole history of Okinawa...

61
00:06:48,127 --> 00:06:50,254
...but the colonel not make mistake.

62
00:06:53,433 --> 00:06:58,302
Explanation: Army teach colonel French
for invasion of Europe...

63
00:06:58,471 --> 00:07:01,099
...then send to Okinawa instead.

64
00:07:01,274 --> 00:07:06,940
One, two, three, four, five, six, seven.

65
00:07:07,113 --> 00:07:08,978
Where's my 8th pair of shorts?

66
00:07:09,148 --> 00:07:12,709
Now colonel gonna yell loud for Sakini.

67
00:07:12,885 --> 00:07:16,685
So I hide. I pretend
to be asleep here. So...

68
00:07:16,856 --> 00:07:18,255
Sakini.

69
00:07:18,424 --> 00:07:22,190
Sakini? Sakini?

70
00:07:22,362 --> 00:07:24,159
Sakini!

71
00:07:27,667 --> 00:07:29,601
Sakini!

72
00:07:30,236 --> 00:07:32,727
- Sakini.
- Oh, good morning, boss.

73
00:07:32,905 --> 00:07:34,202
You sure surprised me, boss.

74
00:07:34,374 --> 00:07:38,140
I want you to tell me why my laundry comes
back every week with one piece missing.

75
00:07:38,311 --> 00:07:41,280
- Gets lost, boss.
- I know it gets lost.

76
00:07:41,447 --> 00:07:43,779
What I wanna find out
is how it gets lost.

77
00:07:43,950 --> 00:07:45,815
Oh, very simple, boss.

78
00:07:45,985 --> 00:07:48,749
Family take laundry
to wash in the stream...

79
00:07:48,921 --> 00:07:53,381
...and while friends exchange greetings,
laundry exchange places.

80
00:07:53,559 --> 00:07:56,960
We run down hill fast as dickens
to catch laundry, boss.

81
00:07:57,130 --> 00:07:59,997
- Well?
- Not run fast enough.

82
00:08:00,933 --> 00:08:03,834
No wonder you people were subjugated
by the Japanese.

83
00:08:04,003 --> 00:08:06,870
If you're not sleeping,
you're running away from work.

84
00:08:07,040 --> 00:08:08,302
Where's your get-up-and-go?

85
00:08:09,842 --> 00:08:11,969
Guess get-up-and-go went, boss.

86
00:08:12,145 --> 00:08:16,138
Well, get up and go down to the officers'
quarters and see if Captain Fisby's arrived.

87
00:08:16,315 --> 00:08:19,113
If he has, tell him to report to me
at once. Hurry.

88
00:08:19,285 --> 00:08:21,276
- Sakini.
- Yes, boss?

89
00:08:21,454 --> 00:08:24,514
You are a civilian employee in the pay
of the United States Army...

90
00:08:24,691 --> 00:08:26,488
...and should dress accordingly.
- Yeah.

91
00:08:26,659 --> 00:08:28,524
Pull your socks up.

92
00:08:29,362 --> 00:08:31,728
Very sorry, boss. Very sorry.

93
00:08:31,898 --> 00:08:36,062
- Socks up. Anything more, boss?
- That'll be all.

94
00:08:38,137 --> 00:08:39,729
Is that as fast as you can walk?

95
00:08:39,906 --> 00:08:44,434
No, no, boss, but to walk any faster,
socks fall down.

96
00:08:49,882 --> 00:08:51,611
- Good morning, sir.
- At ease.

97
00:08:51,784 --> 00:08:54,981
I'm gonna get rid of that interpreter.
He doesn't set a good example.

98
00:08:55,154 --> 00:08:59,591
Colonel, sir, we gotta have someone around
who speaks the language.

99
00:09:00,460 --> 00:09:02,428
You're quite right, sergeant, quite right.

100
00:09:02,595 --> 00:09:04,586
It isn't often I make a mistake.
When I do...

101
00:09:04,764 --> 00:09:07,255
- It's a beaut?
- I wasn't going to say that.

102
00:09:07,433 --> 00:09:10,368
- I was gonna say, "By George, I admit it."
- I'm sorry, sir.

103
00:09:10,536 --> 00:09:12,936
Now, we've got a new officer
reporting this morning.

104
00:09:13,106 --> 00:09:16,439
He's been transferred to us
from Psychological Warfare.

105
00:09:16,609 --> 00:09:18,770
I don't suppose you happen to know
who they are.

106
00:09:18,945 --> 00:09:21,937
Aren't they something at the rear
of the rear echelon?

107
00:09:22,115 --> 00:09:24,709
They're just the cream
of the Army's geniuses.

108
00:09:24,884 --> 00:09:27,318
They're just the brains
behind the fighting heart.

109
00:09:27,487 --> 00:09:30,456
Every man Jack of them has a mind
like a steel trap.

110
00:09:30,623 --> 00:09:32,784
We're lucky to be getting
one of their officers.

111
00:09:32,959 --> 00:09:36,019
- I'll watch my step, sir.
- While we're waiting for Captain Fisby...

112
00:09:36,195 --> 00:09:38,527
...l'd like you to make a note
of new signs I want.

113
00:09:38,698 --> 00:09:41,633
The painter hasn't finished the ones
you ordered yesterday, sir.

114
00:09:41,801 --> 00:09:44,895
There's only one answer to that:
Put on another sign painter.

115
00:09:45,071 --> 00:09:46,299
Yes, sir.

116
00:09:46,472 --> 00:09:51,307
Now, I noticed the men were dancing with
each other in the canteen the other night.

117
00:09:51,477 --> 00:09:54,605
Yes, sir. "No dancing allowed."

118
00:09:54,781 --> 00:09:57,773
I didn't say that, Gregovich.
I don't object to the men dancing.

119
00:09:57,950 --> 00:10:01,681
I want them to enjoy themselves. It doesn't
set a good example for the natives...

120
00:10:01,854 --> 00:10:04,516
...to see noncoms
dancing with enlisted men.

121
00:10:04,690 --> 00:10:06,487
So have a sign posted saying:

122
00:10:06,659 --> 00:10:10,527
"Sergeants are forbidden
to dance with privates."

123
00:10:12,398 --> 00:10:14,798
You might as well take that memo
to the sign painter.

124
00:10:14,967 --> 00:10:16,400
Yes, sir.

125
00:10:32,919 --> 00:10:36,616
- Sakini here, boss.
- Don't ever put your finger on an officer.

126
00:10:36,789 --> 00:10:39,155
- Oh, not all right, boss?
- No.

127
00:10:39,325 --> 00:10:42,021
If you want to announce
your presence, knock.

128
00:10:42,195 --> 00:10:45,289
Can't you natives ever learn anything
about custom?

129
00:10:48,134 --> 00:10:49,795
What do you think you're doing?

130
00:10:49,969 --> 00:10:53,234
Oh, not know, boss. Do what you ask.

131
00:10:53,406 --> 00:10:56,671
Everything in this country
conspires to annoy me.

132
00:10:56,843 --> 00:10:59,243
Well, where is Captain Fisby?

133
00:10:59,412 --> 00:11:04,315
Oh, he come now, boss. I run ahead.
Socks fall down.

134
00:11:06,052 --> 00:11:08,816
Captain Fisby reporting, sir.

135
00:11:08,988 --> 00:11:12,253
Welcome to Team 147.

136
00:11:12,425 --> 00:11:15,223
- I can't tell you how glad I am to have you.
- Thank you, sir.

137
00:11:15,394 --> 00:11:17,794
Frankly, we're so desperate
for officer personnel...

138
00:11:17,964 --> 00:11:21,764
...l'd be glad to see you
even if you had two heads.

139
00:11:21,934 --> 00:11:23,959
That'll be all, Sakini.
You can wait outside.

140
00:11:24,136 --> 00:11:26,969
- Okay.
- Sit down, captain, sit down.

141
00:11:27,139 --> 00:11:32,167
- Thank you. Thank you very much.
- Oh, sorry, boss. I sit by door, boss.

142
00:11:32,345 --> 00:11:34,575
- May as well be comfortable here.
- Yes.

143
00:11:34,747 --> 00:11:35,873
Not sleep.

144
00:11:36,883 --> 00:11:38,077
Have you unpacked?

145
00:11:38,251 --> 00:11:40,811
Oh, yes, sir. I unpacked
as soon as I got in last night.

146
00:11:40,987 --> 00:11:43,922
Well, that's too bad
because you'll have to pack again.

147
00:11:44,090 --> 00:11:46,320
I am sending you to Tobiki at once.

148
00:11:46,492 --> 00:11:48,756
We need a man of your caliber
up there right away.

149
00:11:48,928 --> 00:11:50,520
- Well, thank you.
- I am informed...

150
00:11:50,696 --> 00:11:54,564
...that you requested this transfer
from Psychological Warfare to my outfit.

151
00:11:54,734 --> 00:11:56,759
- May I say that I am honored.
- Yeah.

152
00:11:56,936 --> 00:12:01,896
Well, in all fairness, sir, I think I should
tell you that I was requested to request it.

153
00:12:02,508 --> 00:12:04,908
Oh, may I ask why?

154
00:12:05,077 --> 00:12:06,908
Well, you see, sir...

155
00:12:07,079 --> 00:12:11,345
...it seems that my... My propaganda
to undermine the enemy's morale...

156
00:12:11,517 --> 00:12:14,486
...undermined the staff's morale instead.

157
00:12:14,654 --> 00:12:17,487
How did you get into Psychological Warfare
in the first place?

158
00:12:17,657 --> 00:12:20,785
- I was requested to request a transfer.
- From what?

159
00:12:20,960 --> 00:12:24,293
- The Paymaster General's office.
- What was your duty there?

160
00:12:26,032 --> 00:12:31,060
Well, I had charge
of the payroll-computation machine.

161
00:12:31,771 --> 00:12:34,001
Well, until...

162
00:12:34,173 --> 00:12:37,336
- Until what?
- Well...

163
00:12:38,277 --> 00:12:41,075
You know, machines have always been
my mortal enemy, colonel.

164
00:12:41,247 --> 00:12:44,080
I don't believe that they're inanimate.
They're not inanimate.

165
00:12:44,250 --> 00:12:47,777
- They're full of malice and ill will.
- I asked you what happened, captain.

166
00:12:47,954 --> 00:12:49,546
Yes. Yes, sir.

167
00:12:49,722 --> 00:12:53,317
Well, this machine... This... You know,
the payroll-computation machine?

168
00:12:53,492 --> 00:12:55,357
It made a mistake, it seems...

169
00:12:55,528 --> 00:12:58,554
...of a quarter of a million dollars
in the payroll.

170
00:12:58,731 --> 00:13:03,566
And unfortunately, the men were paid
before the mistake was discovered.

171
00:13:03,736 --> 00:13:08,537
- What did they do to you?
- Oh, they gave me a job licking envelopes.

172
00:13:08,708 --> 00:13:11,506
- And then you asked for a transfer.
- No.

173
00:13:11,677 --> 00:13:14,009
I developed an allergy to glue.

174
00:13:15,614 --> 00:13:19,175
How many outfits in this man's Army
have you been in, captain?

175
00:13:19,352 --> 00:13:22,048
- Let's see, how many are there now, sir?
- Never mind.

176
00:13:22,221 --> 00:13:25,315
I admit disappointment, but not defeat.

177
00:13:25,491 --> 00:13:28,654
I thought you were given to me
in recognition of my work here.

178
00:13:28,828 --> 00:13:32,355
Frankly, I expect to be made
a general soon.

179
00:13:32,531 --> 00:13:36,228
And I want that star
for my wife's crown.

180
00:13:36,402 --> 00:13:39,963
- Naturally, that's very hush-hush.
- Oh, yes, naturally.

181
00:13:40,606 --> 00:13:43,006
Do you know something, sir?
Do you know something?

182
00:13:43,175 --> 00:13:46,872
I just think that perhaps I just wasn't
cut out to be a soldier, that's all.

183
00:13:47,046 --> 00:13:51,608
Captain, none of us was cut out
to be a soldier, but we do the job.

184
00:13:51,784 --> 00:13:55,311
We adjust, we adapt,
we roll with a punch...

185
00:13:55,488 --> 00:13:58,218
...and bring victory home in our teeth.

186
00:14:00,026 --> 00:14:02,551
Do you know what I was
before the war?

187
00:14:03,262 --> 00:14:04,593
A football coach?

188
00:14:05,364 --> 00:14:08,356
I was the Purdy Paper Box Company
of Pottawatomie.

189
00:14:08,534 --> 00:14:10,058
What did I know about foreigners?

190
00:14:10,236 --> 00:14:13,069
But my job is to teach these natives
the meaning of democracy.

191
00:14:13,239 --> 00:14:16,504
And they're gonna learn democracy
if I have to shoot every one of them.

192
00:14:18,077 --> 00:14:20,705
- Yes, sir.
- What did you do before the war?

193
00:14:20,880 --> 00:14:24,077
Oh, I was an associate professor
at Muncie.

194
00:14:24,650 --> 00:14:26,242
- What'd you teach?
- The humanities.

195
00:14:26,419 --> 00:14:29,980
Captain, you're finally getting a job
you're qualified by training to handle:

196
00:14:30,156 --> 00:14:33,717
- Teaching these natives to act human.
- I don't think the humanities are that.

197
00:14:33,893 --> 00:14:36,157
If you can teach one thing,
you can teach another.

198
00:14:36,328 --> 00:14:39,525
This is plan B. Washington has drawn up
full instructions...

199
00:14:39,698 --> 00:14:42,997
...pertaining to the welfare and recovery
of these native villages.

200
00:14:43,169 --> 00:14:47,196
- Consider it your Bible, captain.
- Yes, sir. I'll study it very carefully.

201
00:14:47,373 --> 00:14:49,466
There might be some questions
I'd like to ask.

202
00:14:49,642 --> 00:14:51,735
Washington has anticipated
all your questions.

203
00:14:51,911 --> 00:14:54,505
- Yes, but I was thinking...
- You don't even have to think.

204
00:14:54,680 --> 00:14:57,672
This document relieves you
of that responsibility.

205
00:14:59,118 --> 00:15:01,484
- How is your Japanese?
- Oh, not so very good.

206
00:15:01,654 --> 00:15:04,680
- No, no. Not good, sir.
- Oh, I can see you'll need an interpreter.

207
00:15:04,857 --> 00:15:06,449
Well, l... No, no... Sir...

208
00:15:06,625 --> 00:15:08,559
- I've got just the man for you.
- Colonel?

209
00:15:08,727 --> 00:15:09,955
- Colonel?
- Sakini!

210
00:15:10,129 --> 00:15:13,064
- I could study the language, you know.
- No need, we won the war.

211
00:15:13,232 --> 00:15:15,291
Sakini present, boss.
Socks up, not sleeping.

212
00:15:15,468 --> 00:15:18,096
Sakini, this is Captain Fisby.

213
00:15:18,270 --> 00:15:20,568
- We meet before, boss, you forget.
- Yeah, we met.

214
00:15:20,739 --> 00:15:22,764
I'm assigning you to Captain Fisby.

215
00:15:22,942 --> 00:15:25,604
He's gonna take charge of a village
at the top of Okinawa.

216
00:15:25,778 --> 00:15:29,214
- A village called Tobiki.
- Tobiki, boss.

217
00:15:29,381 --> 00:15:32,817
Very nice place, boss,
but not at top of Okinawa, at bottom.

218
00:15:32,985 --> 00:15:35,818
Don't tell me where the villages
under my command are located.

219
00:15:35,988 --> 00:15:38,786
- I happen to give a course in map reading.
- Very sorry, boss.

220
00:15:38,958 --> 00:15:41,358
But happen to be born in Tobiki.
It's at the bottom.

221
00:15:41,527 --> 00:15:44,963
Then it's time you learned
where you were born.

222
00:15:45,131 --> 00:15:47,998
Oh, very sorry, boss,
but the map upside down.

223
00:15:48,167 --> 00:15:49,498
Oh, yeah. Oh, yeah.

224
00:15:49,668 --> 00:15:52,899
Why doesn't the army learn
how to draw a map properly?

225
00:15:53,072 --> 00:15:54,562
That'll be all, Sakini.

226
00:15:54,740 --> 00:15:57,868
Find Sergeant Gregovich and have him
assign a jeep to Captain Fisby.

227
00:15:58,043 --> 00:16:01,069
Load supplies and the captain's gear.
You'll be leaving at once.

228
00:16:01,247 --> 00:16:06,310
I mention you in prayer to gods, boss.
I wait for you in jeep, captain.

229
00:16:09,788 --> 00:16:13,155
I sometimes think we occupation teams
have it tougher than combat troops.

230
00:16:13,325 --> 00:16:16,453
- Oh, now, I wouldn't say that, sir.
- They have it rough for a while.

231
00:16:16,629 --> 00:16:19,757
But we have the killing daily grind
with no glory in it.

232
00:16:19,932 --> 00:16:21,593
Yes, sir, I know what you mean, sir.

233
00:16:21,767 --> 00:16:25,533
Life itself is a battlefield
