...big Army truck come and leave lovely
lumber and beautiful paint, boss.

921
01:02:28,011 --> 01:02:31,003
That's right. It's for the schoolhouse.
It just can't be done.

922
01:02:31,181 --> 01:02:33,115
- Oh, okay.
- No, it just can't.

923
01:02:37,521 --> 01:02:43,118
They say you very mean to them, boss,
after present... They give you everything.

924
01:02:43,293 --> 01:02:46,922
I'm sorry, I'm sorry, folks.
I'm really very sorry.

925
01:02:47,230 --> 01:02:53,066
Oh, they very sorry too, boss,
because Tobiki like to be proud, boss.

926
01:02:53,236 --> 01:02:54,794
Teahouse give them a face.

927
01:02:55,906 --> 01:02:59,672
It's going to be a fine school. Five sides.

928
01:02:59,876 --> 01:03:03,073
- May I speak, captain-san?
- Yes, of course, Mr. Oshira.

929
01:03:03,246 --> 01:03:07,478
There are lovely teahouses
in the big cities...

930
01:03:07,651 --> 01:03:12,782
...but the men of Tobiki
have never been inside them.

931
01:03:12,956 --> 01:03:15,117
We are too poor.

932
01:03:15,292 --> 01:03:21,754
All of my life I have dreamed
of visiting a teahouse...

933
01:03:21,932 --> 01:03:28,337
...where paper lanterns cast a light
in the lotus pond...

934
01:03:28,538 --> 01:03:34,875
...and the bamboo bells hanging in the pines
tinkle as the breezes brush them.

935
01:03:35,378 --> 01:03:40,406
But this picture is only in my heart.

936
01:03:40,584 --> 01:03:42,745
I may never see it.

937
01:03:42,919 --> 01:03:47,549
I am an old man, sir. I shall die soon.

938
01:03:47,924 --> 01:03:52,293
It is evil for the soul
to depart this world...

939
01:03:52,462 --> 01:03:55,488
...laden with envy or regret.

940
01:03:56,099 --> 01:03:59,626
Give us our teahouse, sir.

941
01:03:59,803 --> 01:04:02,169
Free my soul for death.

942
01:04:09,613 --> 01:04:12,207
Well, we haven't any carpenters.

943
01:04:13,950 --> 01:04:16,851
Daiku-san! Daiku-san!

944
01:04:24,628 --> 01:04:26,186
Oh, boss, what you think?

945
01:04:26,363 --> 01:04:31,892
Mr. Sumata and the papa-san
just come down from mountain right now.

946
01:04:35,906 --> 01:04:38,898
All right, all right, I haven't got a chance.

947
01:04:39,409 --> 01:04:43,140
I guess Uncle Sam is going
into the teahouse business.

948
01:04:49,286 --> 01:04:51,754
Captain Fisby.

949
01:04:53,823 --> 01:04:56,519
Uncle Sam.

950
01:05:17,647 --> 01:05:18,875
Thank you.

951
01:05:19,049 --> 01:05:20,277
Captain Fisby.

952
01:05:20,450 --> 01:05:22,918
<i>Hello. This is Colonel Purdy.</i>

953
01:05:23,086 --> 01:05:24,644
Yes, sir. How are you, colonel?

954
01:05:25,155 --> 01:05:27,487
I want to talk to you
about your progress report.

955
01:05:27,657 --> 01:05:30,490
There's nothing about the schoolhouse.
Did you get the lumber?

956
01:05:30,694 --> 01:05:33,925
Yes, sir. As a matter of fact,
we're using it out there now, sir.

957
01:05:34,097 --> 01:05:37,123
But, colonel, I think we're gonna
have to have some more.

958
01:05:37,300 --> 01:05:40,758
<i>I sent ample according to specifications.
How big a structure you building?</i>

959
01:05:40,937 --> 01:05:44,338
Well, sir, we have to consider expansion,
you know, population increase.

960
01:05:44,541 --> 01:05:46,236
We don't need to consider expansion.

961
01:05:46,409 --> 01:05:48,934
Our troops will be out
of there by the next generation.

962
01:05:49,112 --> 01:05:53,640
Which brings me to another point. What's
this about six kids being born last week?

963
01:05:53,850 --> 01:05:56,910
Well, it's the only thing
to fill the progress report with, sir.

964
01:05:57,120 --> 01:05:59,179
Then you've failed
at your indoctrination.

965
01:05:59,356 --> 01:06:02,291
Don't you know births are entered
under population increases?

966
01:06:02,459 --> 01:06:04,017
They're not considered progress.

967
01:06:04,194 --> 01:06:08,324
No, not children, sir. Kids. Goats.

968
01:06:08,765 --> 01:06:12,531
Something's wrong with this connection.
It sounded just as if you said "goats."

969
01:06:13,103 --> 01:06:15,867
You see, I'm trying to increase
the livestock down here.

970
01:06:16,039 --> 01:06:20,135
Goats? Look, Fisby, suppose some
congressman flew in to inspect our team.

971
01:06:20,310 --> 01:06:22,801
How would I explain
such a report about goats?

972
01:06:23,013 --> 01:06:25,345
<i>The population
of civilians alone concerns us.</i>

973
01:06:25,515 --> 01:06:29,918
<i>I want to know exactly what progress
you've made as outlined in plan B.</i>

974
01:06:30,086 --> 01:06:33,988
<i>- Well, sir, I'm getting along with the people.
- In other words, nothing.</i>

975
01:06:34,290 --> 01:06:37,623
Listen, Fisby, do you know what
Major McEvoy has accomplished in Awasi?

976
01:06:37,794 --> 01:06:39,625
<i>- No, sir.
- Then I'll tell you.</i>

977
01:06:39,796 --> 01:06:42,765
His fourth graders know
the alphabet through M.

978
01:06:42,932 --> 01:06:46,868
His whole village can sing
"God Bless America" in English.

979
01:06:47,237 --> 01:06:48,864
I wish I could say the same.

980
01:06:49,072 --> 01:06:52,735
Well, see that you do. I don't want
any rotten apples in my barrel.

981
01:06:52,909 --> 01:06:55,901
I want to know exactly what
you've accomplished in five weeks.

982
01:06:56,513 --> 01:06:58,606
Well, sir...
Well, we have started an industry.

983
01:06:58,782 --> 01:07:01,683
Matter of fact, we're sending
our first shipment out this week.

984
01:07:01,851 --> 01:07:04,411
- Now, we're making getas. We're...
- Wait a minute.

985
01:07:04,587 --> 01:07:06,179
What in thunder is a geta?

986
01:07:06,389 --> 01:07:08,619
No, it isn't a geta, sir. It's plural. Getas.

987
01:07:08,792 --> 01:07:11,522
Getas, you know, you have to have two.

988
01:07:11,728 --> 01:07:13,889
<i>- Are you breeding some other animal?
- No, no.</i>

989
01:07:14,064 --> 01:07:16,362
You see, you wear them on your feet.

990
01:07:16,533 --> 01:07:20,731
And they're very good for
the metatarsal muscles, colonel.

991
01:07:20,904 --> 01:07:24,237
And now, I have another group.
They're out there making cricket cages.

992
01:07:24,874 --> 01:07:28,833
Captain Fisby,
what kind of cages did you say?

993
01:07:29,012 --> 01:07:30,604
<i>Cricket cages, colonel.</i>

994
01:07:30,814 --> 01:07:32,873
You know, the cricket.
The black bug that...

995
01:07:33,083 --> 01:07:36,416
<i>It rubs its hind legs together.</i>

996
01:07:36,619 --> 01:07:39,179
I think we can sell just thousands
of those cages.

997
01:07:39,355 --> 01:07:43,086
- Of course, we don't supply the cricket.
- Naturally, not.

998
01:07:43,259 --> 01:07:46,888
Captain Fisby,
have you taken your salt pills?

999
01:07:47,630 --> 01:07:50,497
<i>Oh, yes, sir. Every day
at chaya in the pine grove.</i>

1000
01:07:51,334 --> 01:07:53,962
Have you been going out in the sun
without your hat?

1001
01:07:54,170 --> 01:07:57,367
<i>You see, I wear a kasa, sir. It's a...</i>

1002
01:07:57,540 --> 01:08:00,407
The wind blows through the straw.

1003
01:08:00,610 --> 01:08:03,101
<i>It kind of ventilates the brain.</i>

1004
01:08:03,279 --> 01:08:07,773
I see. I see. That'll be all, captain.

1005
01:08:10,386 --> 01:08:12,513
- Gregovich.
- Yes, sir?

1006
01:08:12,689 --> 01:08:15,385
- Who's the psychiatrist over at Awasi?
- Captain McLean?

1007
01:08:15,558 --> 01:08:16,889
Yes. Get him on the phone.

1008
01:08:17,060 --> 01:08:19,995
My man at Tobiki has gone
completely off his rocker.

1009
01:08:26,936 --> 01:08:28,301
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

1010
01:08:28,471 --> 01:08:30,132
Good morning.

1011
01:08:41,417 --> 01:08:43,851
- Hello?
- Good morning.

1012
01:08:44,020 --> 01:08:45,681
Good morning.

1013
01:09:15,151 --> 01:09:17,711
Thank you. Thank you.

1014
01:09:28,631 --> 01:09:30,258
Excuse me.

1015
01:09:30,433 --> 01:09:32,025
I'll see you. Bye.

1016
01:09:39,175 --> 01:09:40,540
Well, who are you?

1017
01:09:41,444 --> 01:09:43,173
- You startled me.
- I'm Captain Fisby.

1018
01:09:43,346 --> 01:09:45,280
Can I do something for you?

1019
01:09:46,616 --> 01:09:50,916
- Oh, well, I'm Captain McLean.
- How do you do, captain?

1020
01:09:51,087 --> 01:09:53,453
There was nobody here, so I came in.

1021
01:09:53,623 --> 01:09:56,683
Medical Corps. I see it. See?

1022
01:09:56,859 --> 01:09:59,828
- What are you doing down here in Tobiki?
- I'm on leave.

1023
01:09:59,996 --> 01:10:01,896
Just thought I'd spend it down here...

1024
01:10:02,065 --> 01:10:05,899
...making some ethnological studies
of the natives.

1025
01:10:06,069 --> 01:10:08,264
- lf you have no objection.
- I don't have any.

1026
01:10:08,438 --> 01:10:10,099
That's in your way. I'll take it.

1027
01:10:10,273 --> 01:10:12,241
I was just examining that.

1028
01:10:12,408 --> 01:10:14,842
- That's my cricket cage.
- Oh, you like crickets?

1029
01:10:15,011 --> 01:10:17,309
I haven't found one,
but I have the cage.

1030
01:10:17,480 --> 01:10:19,710
Matter of fact, I've got two.
Would you like one?

1031
01:10:19,882 --> 01:10:22,680
Oh, no, no, no, thank you.
It's all right.

1032
01:10:22,852 --> 01:10:25,252
- What happened to your uniform?
- Oh, it's around.

1033
01:10:25,421 --> 01:10:29,323
I find getas and a kimono much more
comfortable in this climate.

1034
01:10:29,492 --> 01:10:31,323
But isn't that a bathrobe?

1035
01:10:31,494 --> 01:10:35,453
Well, it passes for a kimono.
Why don't you take your shoes off, captain?

1036
01:10:35,632 --> 01:10:38,066
- Oh, no, thank you. Thank you, no.
- No?

1037
01:10:38,234 --> 01:10:41,670
- I'll just keep them on.
- All right, fine. No objection, of course.

1038
01:10:41,838 --> 01:10:44,306
Sit down, sit down.
In my good chair, my good chair.

1039
01:10:44,474 --> 01:10:47,102
- Thank you.
- Well...

1040
01:10:48,745 --> 01:10:50,337
No?

1041
01:11:00,223 --> 01:11:03,090
May I ask,
what are you building down the road?

1042
01:11:04,527 --> 01:11:06,051
<i>Oh, that's my chaya.</i>

1043
01:11:06,229 --> 01:11:08,527
Gonna be something
to write home about, Mac.

1044
01:11:08,698 --> 01:11:10,996
<i>- A chaya?
- See, if you have a geisha...</i>

1045
01:11:11,167 --> 01:11:14,500
<i>...you gotta have a chaya, you know.</i>

1046
01:11:14,671 --> 01:11:16,138
How have you felt lately, Fisby?

1047
01:11:16,306 --> 01:11:18,797
Mac, I'll tell you something,
I've never felt better.

1048
01:11:18,975 --> 01:11:23,173
I feel reckless and happy
and carefree, and... Well...

1049
01:11:23,346 --> 01:11:25,906
And it all happened the moment
I decided not to build...

1050
01:11:26,082 --> 01:11:28,107
...that pentagon-shaped schoolhouse.
- What?

1051
01:11:28,284 --> 01:11:30,548
The good colonel, he ordered me...
He ordered me...

1052
01:11:30,720 --> 01:11:32,984
...to build a pentagon-shaped
schoolhouse here.

1053
01:11:33,156 --> 01:11:34,555
The natives wanted a teahouse.

1054
01:11:34,724 --> 01:11:37,124
Would you believe
one of them gave me a geisha girl?

1055
01:11:37,293 --> 01:11:40,990
So I decided that I was going
to give them what they want.

1056
01:11:41,164 --> 01:11:43,564
I guess it sounds kind of crazy,
doesn't it?

1057
01:11:43,733 --> 01:11:46,998
Well, yes and no.

1058
01:11:47,170 --> 01:11:48,899
You know, these are wonderful people.

1059
01:11:49,072 --> 01:11:52,041
Wonderful people
with a... A strange sense of beauty.

1060
01:11:52,208 --> 01:11:54,267
Hard-working when there's a purpose.

1061
01:11:54,444 --> 01:11:55,741
You know what they're doing?

1062
01:11:55,912 --> 01:11:58,745
They're making cricket cages
and lacquerware and chopsticks...

1063
01:11:58,915 --> 01:12:00,382
...to sell as souvenirs.

1064
01:12:00,550 --> 01:12:03,815
Don't let anybody ever, ever tell you
that these people are lazy.

1065
01:12:03,986 --> 01:12:08,320
- That's... Oh, I see.
- No, you don't. You don't.

1066
01:12:08,491 --> 01:12:10,322
- Oh, I see.
- No, you don't, no, no.

1067
01:12:10,493 --> 01:12:11,960
You will when you study them.

1068
01:12:12,128 --> 01:12:13,823
- You're building a teahouse.
- Yes.

1069
01:12:13,996 --> 01:12:16,157
And next, I'm gonna go out
and test that soil.

1070
01:12:16,332 --> 01:12:18,800
See if it won't grow something
besides sweet potatoes.

1071
01:12:18,968 --> 01:12:20,492
I'll send for some nitrate...

1072
01:12:20,670 --> 01:12:23,138
...some DDT and chemicals...
- Chemicals?

1073
01:12:23,306 --> 01:12:24,773
Yes.

1074
01:12:26,242 --> 01:12:28,767
- You want to poison these people?
- What? No.

1075
01:12:28,945 --> 01:12:31,140
- Look, captain...
- What? What?

1076
01:12:31,314 --> 01:12:32,941
I'm sorry.

1077
01:12:33,116 --> 01:12:36,051
You just touched on a subject
that's very close to my heart.

1078
01:12:36,219 --> 01:12:37,686
- Gardening.
- Yes?

1079
01:12:39,422 --> 01:12:41,822
I've been on the point
of giving up my career...

1080
01:12:41,991 --> 01:12:44,357
...just so I could set up
an experimental farm...

1081
01:12:44,527 --> 01:12:48,156
...somewhere where I could raise
vegetables organically, nature's way.

1082
01:12:48,331 --> 01:12:51,494
No poisons, no chemicals.

1083
01:12:51,667 --> 01:12:53,862
Let me tell you something, captain.

1084
01:12:54,036 --> 01:12:56,504
Chemicals will kill all your earthworms.

1085
01:12:56,672 --> 01:13:00,540
- And earthworms aerate your soil.
- They do?

1086
01:13:00,710 --> 01:13:02,974
Do you know that the earthworm
leaves castings...

1087
01:13:03,146 --> 01:13:05,410
...eight times its own weight every day?

1088
01:13:05,581 --> 01:13:06,809
That much?

1089
01:13:06,983 --> 01:13:08,814
Organic gar... It's the only thing.

1090
01:13:08,985 --> 01:13:13,319
Compost. Manure. But no chemicals.

1091
01:13:13,489 --> 01:13:15,821
- You know a lot about this, I can tell.
- Well...

1092
01:13:15,992 --> 01:13:17,050
- Well, l...
- You do.

1093
01:13:17,226 --> 01:13:20,423
I subscribed to all the farm journals
for years, you know.

1094
01:13:20,596 --> 01:13:24,088
Mac, listen to me,
I've got the... I've got the greatest idea.

1095
01:13:24,267 --> 01:13:28,135
While you're here, you could really do us
a big favor. A big service, mind you.

1096
01:13:28,304 --> 01:13:30,204
You could sort of take over supervision.

1097
01:13:30,373 --> 01:13:34,503
Establish a kind of a... What do you call it?
An experimental station.

1098
01:13:35,645 --> 01:13:37,545
Well...

1099
01:13:40,016 --> 01:13:43,315
- Oh, I haven't got the time.
- Take time, man. Take time.

1100
01:13:43,486 --> 01:13:45,750
This is a chance
to put your theories into facts.

1101
01:13:45,922 --> 01:13:48,584
These are not theories.
These are proved facts.

1102
01:13:48,758 --> 01:13:51,249
Just tell us how to go about it.
That's all, Mac.

1103
01:13:51,427 --> 01:13:54,021
- Is your soil acid or alkaline?
- Oh, golly, I don't know.

1104
01:13:54,197 --> 01:13:56,995
- That's the first thing to find out.
- You're the man we need.

1105
01:13:57,166 --> 01:13:59,999
- You're a genius.
- I'll want plenty of manure.

1106
01:14:00,169 --> 01:14:04,299
- You'll get it.
- And I want to set this program up scientif...

1107
01:14:04,974 --> 01:14:08,569
- What's the matter? What is it?
- I wish I had my books, my seed...

1108
01:14:08,744 --> 01:14:11,269
Oh, I've got a stack
of seed catalogs that high.

1109
01:14:11,781 --> 01:14:13,681
- You have?
- Oh, man, and l...

1110
01:14:13,850 --> 01:14:16,683
Well, let's sit down here. Sit down.
You know what you can do?

1111
01:14:16,853 --> 01:14:19,754
You can write a list of those seeds,
catalogs, and books.

1112
01:14:19,922 --> 01:14:22,413
- And get airstrip to fly them in.
- Can you do that?

1113
01:14:22,592 --> 01:14:25,425
Can I do it? Sit down. Can I do it?
Of course, I can do it.

1114
01:14:25,595 --> 01:14:28,564
- Make the list...
- Every spring I've made lists of seeds.

1115
01:14:28,731 --> 01:14:31,029
I never had any soil to put them in.

1116
01:14:31,200 --> 01:14:32,997
Now I can actually germinate.

1117
01:14:33,169 --> 01:14:35,535
Make the list right now
and we'll get started.

1118
01:14:35,705 --> 01:14:38,037
- Corn: golden bantam.
- Yes.

1119
01:14:38,207 --> 01:14:39,606
- And Country Gentleman.
- Right.

1120
01:14:39,775 --> 01:14:41,106
- Hybrid.
- I got to check...

1121
01:14:41,277 --> 01:14:42,574
- Hybrid.
- Hybrid? Yes.

1122
01:14:42,745 --> 01:14:44,838
Gotta check with
my Department of Agriculture.

1123
01:14:45,014 --> 01:14:46,504
I'll be back this afternoon...

1124
01:14:46,682 --> 01:14:49,515
...because you and l...
We'll have tea in the pine grove, Mac.

1125
01:14:49,685 --> 01:14:52,916
We have tea in the pine grove
every afternoon when the sun goes down.

1126
01:14:53,089 --> 01:14:55,580
Cucumbers: Early Green Prolific.

1127
01:14:56,425 --> 01:14:58,359
And radishes.

1128
01:14:58,528 --> 01:15:00,519
Crimson giant.

1129
01:15:01,163 --> 01:15:03,393
Crimson giant.

1130
01:15:05,768 --> 01:15:08,396
- There's no answer, sir.
- What do you mean, no answer?

1131
01:15:08,571 --> 01:15:12,632
Well, keep trying, I'm not the kind of a man
to take no answer for an answer.

1132
01:15:15,177 --> 01:15:17,645
<i>Tomatoes: Ponderosa Earlyiana.</i>

1133
01:15:17,813 --> 01:15:19,212
Watermelon:

1134
01:15:19,382 --> 01:15:22,283
All American Gold Medal.

1135
01:15:24,320 --> 01:15:26,083
Hello.

1136
01:15:26,255 --> 01:15:29,281
<i>- Who is this?
- This is Captain McLean.</i>

1137
01:15:29,458 --> 01:15:31,756
This is Colonel Purdy.

1138
01:15:31,928 --> 01:15:35,125
<i>- Can you talk?
- Why not?</i>

1139
01:15:35,731 --> 01:15:38,962
I'm anxious to hear your report
on you-know-who.

1140
01:15:39,135 --> 01:15:41,035
<i>On who?</i>

1141
01:15:41,203 --> 01:15:43,694
Captain Fisby.
The man I sent you down to examine.

1142
01:15:46,375 --> 01:15:50,277
Well, colonel, looks like
I'll have to be down here several weeks.

1143
01:15:50,646 --> 01:15:51,874
Several weeks?

1144
01:15:52,048 --> 01:15:54,778
<i>- Well, Rome wasn't built in a day.
- What?</i>

1145
01:15:54,951 --> 01:15:57,579
I said, Rome wasn't built in a day.

1146
01:15:57,753 --> 01:15:59,118
<i>Well, you're the doctor.</i>

1147
01:15:59,288 --> 01:16:01,313
Thank you,
but I expect to work miracles.

1148
01:16:01,891 --> 01:16:06,294
<i>Splendid. Is there anything I can send?
Some old Adventure magazines or anything?</i>

1149
01:16:06,696 --> 01:16:10,462
Say, colonel,
there are a couple of books I'd like.

1150
01:16:11,100 --> 01:16:13,330
I don't think you could get them.

1151
01:16:13,502 --> 01:16:14,867
<i>You name them.</i>

1152
01:16:15,037 --> 01:16:18,006
<i>Well, one is the
Principles of Pea Production...</i>

1153
01:16:19,475 --> 01:16:24,811
<i>...and the other one,
the Do's and Don'ts of Cabbage Culture.</i>

1154
01:16:24,981 --> 01:16:26,243
<i>Oh, and, colonel...</i>

1155
01:16:26,882 --> 01:16:29,316
...think you could lay your hands
on a soil-test kit?

1156
01:16:30,019 --> 01:16:32,852
<i>- A what?
- A soil-test kit.</i>

1157
01:16:33,456 --> 01:16:35,515
I wanna test the soil here,
see if it's sour.

1158
01:16:36,726 --> 01:16:38,057
Sour, did you say?

1159
01:16:38,227 --> 01:16:41,492
Well, yeah, if soil is sour,
your seeds won't germinate.

1160
01:16:44,734 --> 01:16:48,830
And, oh, I'd love to lay my hands
on some bees.

1161
01:16:50,239 --> 01:16:51,968
Something's wrong
with the connection.

1162
01:16:52,141 --> 01:16:54,439
And I'm gonna have
to take some time out.

1163
01:16:54,610 --> 01:16:57,010
I gotta build up this soil,
you know, with manure.

1164
01:16:58,247 --> 01:17:00,681
<i>- Did you say manure?
- Yeah.</i>

1165
01:17:00,850 --> 01:17:02,579
Nature's way.

1166
01:17:02,752 --> 01:17:06,552
Oh, I've lost faith in chemicals.
You kill all your worms.

1167
01:17:06,722 --> 01:17:08,713
Oh, let me tell you, colonel...

1168
01:17:08,891 --> 01:17:11,359
...when you kill a worm,
you're killing a friend.

1169
01:17:20,236 --> 01:17:21,533
Hello?

1170
01:17:22,805 --> 01:17:24,568
- Gregovich.
- Yes, sir?

1171
01:17:24,740 --> 01:17:27,766
- Where's plan B?
- What did you want, sir?

1172
01:17:27,943 --> 01:17:31,242
I wanna see who I send
to analyze an analyst.

1173
01:17:36,485 --> 01:17:38,043
That's hot water.

1174
01:17:38,220 --> 01:17:40,484
- Hot water.
- Hot water.

1175
01:17:40,656 --> 01:17:42,681
That's it.

1176
01:17:47,930 --> 01:17:49,522
Hey. Hey.

1177
01:17:49,699 --> 01:17:51,428
Mac, Mac, come on, over here.

1178
01:17:51,600 --> 01:17:53,659
- Over here.
- I got a list of seeds here.

1179
01:17:53,836 --> 01:17:58,569
Put some more hot water in the pot
because we have a guest here.

1180
01:17:58,741 --> 01:18:01,335
This is Lotus Blossom.

1181
01:18:01,510 --> 01:18:04,775
- How do you do?
- That's the geisha girl I told you about.

1182
01:18:05,848 --> 01:18:08,408
- She can't speak English.
- She doesn't need to.

1183
01:18:08,584 --> 01:18:11,212
No? Oh, hey. The seeds. You sit...

1184
01:18:11,387 --> 01:18:13,787
- Sit down here, will you?
- Thank you, I'd like that.

1185
01:18:13,956 --> 01:18:17,153
Have some of this. You know something?
That's real jasmine tea.

1186
01:18:17,326 --> 01:18:18,588
- Really?
- Here's a pillow.

1187
01:18:18,761 --> 01:18:20,956
- Thank you.
- Take off your shoes.

1188
01:18:23,232 --> 01:18:26,326
- Now, about those seeds...
- No.

1189
01:18:26,502 --> 01:18:29,062
Now we're gonna sit here
and watch the sun go down.

1190
01:18:29,238 --> 01:18:32,469
And we're gonna contemplate
the end of the day.

1191
01:19:38,277 --> 01:19:40,177
Look, captain, I'm sorry to interrupt.

1192
01:19:40,879 --> 01:19:43,871
Could you let me have
a couple of boys to help me in the fields?

1193
01:19:44,049 --> 01:19:46,847
Darn Japanese beetles
are eating up all my Chinese peas.

1194
01:19:47,019 --> 01:19:50,284
All right, I'll get Sakini to get
a couple boys to help you, all right?

1195
01:19:50,455 --> 01:19:52,946
- Oh, good, thanks.
- Alrighty. Now, Mac?

1196
01:19:53,125 --> 01:19:55,821
Sit down, Mac, and listen for a while.

1197
01:19:55,994 --> 01:19:58,485
Lotus Blossom, will you sing again
for my friend Mac?

1198
01:19:58,664 --> 01:20:01,690
- Thank you.
- Mac, but quiet, huh?

1199
01:20:01,867 --> 01:20:03,266
All right.

1200
01:20:03,435 --> 01:20:05,528
Here we go.

1201
01:20:20,986 --> 01:20:22,681
Boss?

1202
01:20:22,855 --> 01:20:26,484
Very sorry to interrupt lovely song, boss,
but emergency out here.

1203
01:20:26,658 --> 01:20:28,057
What's the matter?

1204
01:20:28,227 --> 01:20:29,626
Everyone come back, boss.

1205
01:20:30,195 --> 01:20:33,221
All right. We better go see
how they made out with the souvenirs.

1206
01:20:34,867 --> 01:20:38,030
Yeah, put it up here so we can use this.

1207
01:20:38,670 --> 01:20:39,932
All right.

1208
01:20:40,105 --> 01:20:43,074
All right? Come on, let's go.

1209
01:20:46,011 --> 01:20:48,536
What's this?
Now what's happened here?

1210
01:20:48,714 --> 01:20:50,841
All the souvenirs come back, boss.

1211
01:20:51,016 --> 01:20:53,348
What do you mean?
You mean to say they didn't sell?

1212
01:20:53,518 --> 01:20:56,783
No, the soldiers who look
at the straw hats say:

1213
01:20:56,955 --> 01:20:58,923
"What you think we are? Hayseed?"

1214
01:20:59,091 --> 01:21:01,525
Mr. Oshira, look,
you were at Yatoda, what happened?

1215
01:21:01,693 --> 01:21:03,354
The Navy always spends money.

1216
01:21:03,528 --> 01:21:05,723
Sailor said, "How much you want?"

1217
01:21:05,898 --> 01:21:08,696
- I said, "25 yen."
- That's good.

1218
01:21:08,867 --> 01:21:11,267
They say, "Oh, too much.

1219
01:21:11,436 --> 01:21:15,065
Can get better in five-and-ten-cent store.

1220
01:21:15,240 --> 01:21:17,970
- Give you one nickel."
- Didn't you tell them, Mr. Oshira...

1221
01:21:18,143 --> 01:21:20,771
...that every one of those cups
is handmade?

1222
01:21:20,946 --> 01:21:23,540
They say, not care.

1223
01:21:23,715 --> 01:21:26,912
They say at home, have big machine...

1224
01:21:27,085 --> 01:21:30,714
...make ten cups every minute.

1225
01:21:31,189 --> 01:21:36,126
They say, "Take nickel or jump in lake."

1226
01:21:36,395 --> 01:21:37,623
How do you like that?

1227
01:21:37,796 --> 01:21:39,696
Boss, you gonna stop work
on the teahouse?

1228
01:21:39,865 --> 01:21:41,992
No, we're not going to stop work on...

1229
01:21:42,167 --> 01:21:45,193
They're gonna get that teahouse
if they don't get anything else.

1230
01:21:45,370 --> 01:21:48,999
By golly, you can tell them that I'm very
proud of that work that they've done.

1231
01:21:49,174 --> 01:21:54,271
I'm so proud. And you can tell them too,
Sakini, that I'm very proud of them.

1232
01:21:54,446 --> 01:21:56,414
No, I am, I really am.

1233
01:21:56,581 --> 01:21:59,550
And I don't understand this.
No, no, no, I don't understand this.

1234
01:21:59,718 --> 01:22:00,946
I don't understand this.

1235
01:22:01,119 --> 01:22:05,385
Boss, they sure wish they could make some
money to spend in the teahouse, boss.

1236
01:22:05,557 --> 01:22:08,549
Because they not like
to go poor like beggar.

1237
01:22:08,727 --> 01:22:10,388
I know, I know.

1238
01:22:14,733 --> 01:22:18,726
See, he say, boss, it not your fault
no one buy souvenir.

1239
01:22:22,674 --> 01:22:24,767
Well, they going home
to get drunk now, boss.

1240
01:22:24,943 --> 01:22:28,674
You know, I don't blame them, Sakini.
If I could find something to drink...

1241
01:22:28,847 --> 01:22:30,610
Wait a minute. Wait a minute, folks.

1242
01:22:30,782 --> 01:22:32,409
What are they gonna get drunk on?

1243
01:22:32,584 --> 01:22:34,381
Oh, they got nothing but brandy, boss.

1244
01:22:34,553 --> 01:22:36,987
- Nothing but brandy?
- Nothing but brandy?

1245
01:22:37,155 --> 01:22:39,487
How are you gonna manage
to get brandy?

1246
01:22:39,658 --> 01:22:42,752
Oh, we make a very fine brandy, boss,
from sweet potatoes.

1247
01:22:42,928 --> 01:22:44,555
Been making for generations.

1248
01:22:44,730 --> 01:22:46,994
You make brandy yourself?

1249
01:22:47,165 --> 01:22:50,532
Yeah, sure, boss.
You want to taste some?

1250
01:22:53,839 --> 01:22:57,002
- Here you are, boss.
- Mac, Mac, my dear friend, Mac.

1251
01:22:57,175 --> 01:23:01,134
If this stuff is only halfway good, we're...
Oh, man, we're really in business.

1252
01:23:01,313 --> 01:23:03,372
This is one thing our men...
They'll buy this.

1253
01:23:03,548 --> 01:23:07,040
It may not be any good. You know,
some things even our troops won't drink.

1254
01:23:07,219 --> 01:23:08,846
- Well.
- Take a sip, boss.

1255
01:23:09,021 --> 01:23:11,148
I wanna smell it.

1256
01:23:13,525 --> 01:23:16,358
- Obviously it has a kick.
- Yeah.

1257
01:23:16,528 --> 01:23:18,291
How old is this stuff, Sakini?

1258
01:23:20,932 --> 01:23:23,332
- Seven years?
- No, seven days, boss.

1259
01:23:23,502 --> 01:23:26,494
Oh, no, no, I mean, it wouldn't
smell like that in seven days.

1260
01:23:26,671 --> 01:23:28,070
They make it last week, boss.

1261
01:23:28,240 --> 01:23:30,708
Here, you try it, will you, Mac?
You're a medical man.

1262
01:23:30,876 --> 01:23:32,571
- You give it a try.
- What?

1263
01:23:34,913 --> 01:23:36,471
- You first.
- No, you're my guest.

1264
01:23:36,648 --> 01:23:38,843
I waive the honor.

1265
01:23:39,351 --> 01:23:41,751
You know, anybody ever die
or go blind from this?

1266
01:23:41,920 --> 01:23:44,388
We not dead. We not blind.

1267
01:23:44,556 --> 01:23:48,492
- Of course not. You see? Come on, Mac.
- They've worked up an immunity.

1268
01:23:48,660 --> 01:23:52,027
You see, I don't wanna kill one of
my own countrymen, you know?

1269
01:23:52,197 --> 01:23:55,223
There must be some way to test this,
isn't there, without me...?

1270
01:23:55,400 --> 01:23:56,867
There isn't, huh?

1271
01:23:57,035 --> 01:23:59,026
Well.

1272
01:24:02,641 --> 01:24:05,007
Sakini, get me Elsa Maxwell.

1273
01:24:05,177 --> 01:24:08,044
- One goat coming up, boss.
- Elsa Maxwell. That's who we need.

1274
01:24:08,213 --> 01:24:11,011
That's Higa Jiga's goat, you know?
We'll test it on her, see?

1275
01:24:11,183 --> 01:24:13,845
Well, what are you gonna prove?
Goats have hardy stomachs.

1276
01:24:14,019 --> 01:24:16,647
No, look, if this brandy...

1277
01:24:16,822 --> 01:24:20,690
If this passes the goat test,
we're really in business, you know?

1278
01:24:20,859 --> 01:24:24,795
You know why? No Marine will ever admit
that his stomach is weaker than a goat's.

1279
01:24:24,963 --> 01:24:27,591
Hey, boss, you gonna make
a guinea pig of goat?

1280
01:24:27,766 --> 01:24:30,667
Yeah, give me something to put it in.
Anything at all will do.

1281
01:24:30,836 --> 01:24:34,397
- Helmet?
- That's fine. That's fine. That's just fine.

1282
01:24:35,540 --> 01:24:38,634
- Oh, Elsa Maxwell very lucky goat, boss.
- Easy, easy.

1283
01:24:38,810 --> 01:24:40,072
Hold her head, Sakini.

1284
01:24:40,245 --> 01:24:43,612
All right, doctor,
proceed in the name of science.

1285
01:24:44,950 --> 01:24:47,077
Take it easy. Take it easy.

1286
01:24:47,252 --> 01:24:51,120
We're either gonna have an industry
or goat meat for dinner.

1287
01:24:52,157 --> 01:24:54,682
- What are you doing?
- Oh, not too much.

1288
01:24:57,896 --> 01:25:00,262
She likes that.

1289
01:25:00,432 --> 01:25:02,559
Hey. Hey.

1290
01:25:02,734 --> 01:25:04,258
She all right? All right?

1291
01:25:04,436 --> 01:25:06,336
What do you think, doc?

1292
01:25:06,505 --> 01:25:09,838
It doesn't seem to affect her.
Reflexes okay.

1293
01:25:10,008 --> 01:25:13,444
Well, here goes.

1294
01:25:31,463 --> 01:25:33,260
Hey.

1295
01:25:33,798 --> 01:25:35,026
Where you going, boss?

1296
01:25:35,200 --> 01:25:39,398
I'm about to form the cooperative
brewing company of Tobiki.

1297
01:25:59,457 --> 01:26:01,254
Officers' Club at Awasi, please.

1298
01:26:01,426 --> 01:26:03,986
- We gonna make brandy, boss?
- I'll tell you in a minute.

1299
01:26:04,162 --> 01:26:06,926
Officers' Club at Awasi?
Captain Fisby speaking at Tobiki.

1300
01:26:07,098 --> 01:26:08,861
Yeah, oh, major? Major, this is Fisby.

1301
01:26:09,034 --> 01:26:11,025
Yeah, you know,
when I was with your unit...

1302
01:26:11,203 --> 01:26:14,172
...we had a hard time
keeping a supply of liquor at the club?

1303
01:26:14,339 --> 01:26:18,173
You remember? Yeah, well, major,
I think I have stumbled on to something...

1304
01:26:18,343 --> 01:26:20,140
...that might be of interest to you.

1305
01:26:20,512 --> 01:26:25,540
Yes, as you know, Tobiki
is the heart of the brandy industry.

1306
01:26:25,717 --> 01:26:28,242
<i>Brandy! Did you say brandy?</i>

1307
01:26:28,420 --> 01:26:29,978
Yes, brandy.

1308
01:26:30,155 --> 01:26:32,521
Look up the word sweet potato
in my dictionary.

1309
01:26:32,691 --> 01:26:36,559
See if there's a fancier word
for sweet potato.

1310
01:26:36,728 --> 01:26:39,094
Oh, I'm here, major, yes, here I am.

1311
01:26:39,264 --> 01:26:43,257
Yeah, now, look, major, I might be able
to supply some of that brandy to you...

1312
01:26:43,435 --> 01:26:47,701
...that is, of course, if you're willing to pay
the price and you keep the source secret.

1313
01:26:47,872 --> 01:26:49,169
Yes.

1314
01:26:49,341 --> 01:26:51,536
Oh, they've been making
it here for generations.

1315
01:26:51,710 --> 01:26:55,840
Oh, yes. As a matter of fact, I'm sure
you've never tasted anything quite like it.

1316
01:26:56,014 --> 01:26:57,413
Hold on a minute, major.

1317
01:26:57,582 --> 01:27:02,679
<i>The Haitian name for sweet potato
is B-A-T-A-T-A, batata.</i>

1318
01:27:02,854 --> 01:27:08,850
Major, you've heard of
Seven Star Batata, haven't you?

1319
01:27:09,694 --> 01:27:12,561
Oh, well, they make it here
in Tobiki. Yes.

1320
01:27:12,731 --> 01:27:14,756
Seven Star got him, I think.

1321
01:27:14,933 --> 01:27:18,027
Brandy eight- or ten-day-old, better.
Nine- or ten-day-old.

1322
01:27:18,203 --> 01:27:23,937
Major, we also have Eight Star Batata,
and we have Ten Star.

1323
01:27:24,109 --> 01:27:27,476
Of course, the Ten Star. Mind you,
that comes a bit more expensive. Yes?

1324
01:27:27,646 --> 01:27:30,114
That will run you...

1325
01:27:30,982 --> 01:27:34,611
...100-occupation yen a gallon.

1326
01:27:34,786 --> 01:27:36,083
Delivered.

1327
01:27:36,254 --> 01:27:37,619
Yes.

1328
01:27:37,789 --> 01:27:40,451
What? How many?

1329
01:27:40,625 --> 01:27:42,525
Five gallons. Yes.

1330
01:27:42,694 --> 01:27:44,719
Five gallons will be delivered
in one week.

1331
01:27:44,896 --> 01:27:48,992
It'll be delivered by
our Department of Agriculture.

1332
01:27:49,167 --> 01:27:52,500
Yeah, right. You're welcome, sir. Right.

1333
01:27:56,541 --> 01:27:59,339
All right. All right, let's...

1334
01:28:00,145 --> 01:28:01,373
Hello?

1335
01:28:01,546 --> 01:28:03,343
News kind of gets around fast, huh?

1336
01:28:03,515 --> 01:28:05,346
Hello?

1337
01:28:05,950 --> 01:28:10,284
GHQ. H... GHQ PX?

1338
01:28:10,455 --> 01:28:12,423
Yes. Yes.

1339
01:28:14,092 --> 01:28:15,889
- Thirty gallons?
- No.

1340
01:28:16,061 --> 01:28:17,722
COD?

1341
01:28:17,896 --> 01:28:19,329
Yes. Right.

1342
01:28:19,497 --> 01:28:20,725
It'll be there.

1343
01:28:20,899 --> 01:28:24,596
- Right. Thank you.
- Thirty gallons.

1344
01:28:27,172 --> 01:28:28,400
Let's go to work, huh?

1345
01:28:28,573 --> 01:28:31,804
I don't have to tell you.
Let's go to work.

1346
01:28:31,976 --> 01:28:33,841
Wait!

1347
01:28:34,012 --> 01:28:35,741
Wait.

1348
01:28:35,914 --> 01:28:37,814
Wait.

1349
01:28:47,625 --> 01:28:50,287
I've got my cricket.

1350
01:29:08,847 --> 01:29:11,077
Put a label on that one.

1351
01:29:12,183 --> 01:29:16,517
Seiko. Seiko, 15O more gallons
to the Naval Officers' Club, Big Koza.

1352
01:29:16,688 --> 01:29:18,986
COD. Take it away.

1353
01:29:19,157 --> 01:29:21,557
Yatoda!

1354
01:29:31,136 --> 01:29:33,161
Hey, Sakini, what are they doing here?

1355
01:29:34,506 --> 01:29:37,202
We're diverting water for a lotus pond.

1356
01:29:37,375 --> 01:29:39,036
Can't have a teahouse
without a pond.

1357
01:29:39,210 --> 01:29:40,700
Yeah, where's your goldfish?

1358
01:29:40,879 --> 01:29:44,212
You have a lotus pond,
you gotta have goldfish.

1359
01:29:49,421 --> 01:29:50,911
Hey, boss.

1360
01:29:51,089 --> 01:29:55,958
Everyone send me to bring you
to teahouse opening, boss.

1361
01:29:57,228 --> 01:29:58,820
Mac, look. Isn't that something?

1362
01:29:58,997 --> 01:30:00,931
This first-class, boss.

1363
01:30:01,399 --> 01:30:03,993
Hey, boy, that's really something, Sakini.

1364
01:30:04,169 --> 01:30:05,898
How about that?

1365
01:30:06,070 --> 01:30:07,662
- Well, come on, let's go.
- Lead on.

1366
01:30:07,839 --> 01:30:09,431
Okay.

1367
01:30:56,955 --> 01:30:59,480
Take shoes off, boss.

1368
01:31:14,506 --> 01:31:15,803
Thank you.

1369
01:31:15,974 --> 01:31:17,908
Good evening.

1370
01:31:19,110 --> 01:31:22,807
Boss, you sit here.
Lotus Blossom gonna dance in your honor.

1371
01:31:22,981 --> 01:31:25,541
Hey, Mac, you hear that?
She's gonna dance.

1372
01:31:25,717 --> 01:31:28,277
Come on. Sit down, Mac, you farmer.
This is in my honor.

1373
01:31:28,453 --> 01:31:33,015
How can I stall Purdy
so I can stay down here?

1374
01:31:33,191 --> 01:31:35,591
I'll have a relapse for you.

1375
01:35:39,403 --> 01:35:42,065
Chrysanthemum bud
in full bloom now, boss.

1376
01:35:42,240 --> 01:35:46,404
And now, happy birthday.

1377
01:35:46,577 --> 01:35:47,839
Very good.

1378
01:35:48,012 --> 01:35:50,276
Well, I'll be.

1379
01:35:51,549 --> 01:35:54,712
- How did you know?
- I gave you away.

1380
01:35:56,053 --> 01:36:00,285
Boss, now everyone like
to show appreciation, boss.

1381
01:36:04,629 --> 01:36:06,563
Happy birthday.

1382
01:36:06,731 --> 01:36:09,598
How very lovely you are.

1383
01:36:14,372 --> 01:36:16,704
And a happy, happy to you.

1384
01:36:18,643 --> 01:36:19,871
Yeah.

1385
01:36:31,622 --> 01:36:33,817
Oh, boss, you know what you do?

1386
01:36:34,091 --> 01:36:35,991
It called for flowers, sort of, you know?

1387
01:36:36,160 --> 01:36:38,128
That mean you give your heart to her.

1388
01:36:38,296 --> 01:36:41,129
Well, I do. We all do, huh?

1389
01:36:41,299 --> 01:36:42,994
Wasn't it beautiful, Mac?

1390
01:36:43,167 --> 01:36:46,295
<i>She can dance
in my cha ya any day.</i>

1391
01:36:52,510 --> 01:36:54,535
Pardon me, sir.

1392
01:36:57,648 --> 01:37:00,845
- Are you sure this is Tobiki village?
- According to the map, sir.

1393
01:37:01,018 --> 01:37:03,816
- The place seems deserted.
- There was a light over there.

1394
01:37:03,988 --> 01:37:05,979
Come on.

1395
01:37:09,060 --> 01:37:12,325
What? What is this?
Sakini, what do they want?

1396
01:37:12,496 --> 01:37:17,058
- They want you and doctor to sing song.
- Sing? No.

1397
01:37:17,235 --> 01:37:19,362
All right, come on, come on, Mac.

1398
01:37:19,537 --> 01:37:21,767
Come on, we're gonna sing something.

1399
01:37:21,939 --> 01:37:24,066
How about
"Deep in the Heart of Texas"?

1400
01:37:24,242 --> 01:37:26,472
Why not? There aren't any
Texans here are there?

1401
01:37:26,644 --> 01:37:29,807
We're gonna have some fun now.
Sakini, look. You know, I want...

1402
01:37:29,981 --> 01:37:33,940
They're gonna help. When we clap and sing
"Deep in the Heart of Texas," they join.

1403
01:37:34,118 --> 01:37:37,087
Oh, I know that song.
Very nice, boss. We demonstrate.

1404
01:37:37,255 --> 01:37:39,280
- What is it?
- Stars at night.

1405
01:37:48,966 --> 01:37:51,196
- Deep in the heart of Texas.
- Deep in the heart...

1406
01:37:51,369 --> 01:37:55,135
Deep in the heart of Texas.

1407
01:37:55,306 --> 01:37:56,671
Then we clap four times.

1408
01:37:59,110 --> 01:38:01,044
Hey, we're all ready. Hey, we're ready.

1409
01:38:01,212 --> 01:38:04,204
All right. You ready on the left?
Ready on the right. Here we go.

1410
01:38:23,301 --> 01:38:24,598
Yes, sir.

1411
01:38:37,748 --> 01:38:39,340
Captain Fisby!

1412
01:38:44,188 --> 01:38:45,746
What in the name...?

1413
01:38:46,424 --> 01:38:47,550
What?

1414
01:38:48,059 --> 01:38:50,527
I see you, Fisby.

1415
01:38:50,728 --> 01:38:52,855
Fisby, I see you.

1416
01:38:54,732 --> 01:38:57,428
Where are you?
Where are you? Where are you?

1417
01:38:57,601 --> 01:39:01,367
Fisby. Fisby.
Come out here. Come out of here.

1418
01:39:02,840 --> 01:39:04,205
Come out of here.

1419
01:39:08,846 --> 01:39:10,404
Sit down!

1420
01:39:10,581 --> 01:39:14,347
How many lectures have you delivered
to the village children on democratic theory?

1421
01:39:14,518 --> 01:39:17,214
- Well, now, let me see, sir.
- Four, five?

1422
01:39:17,388 --> 01:39:18,878
No, no, no, it wasn't that many.

1423
01:39:19,056 --> 01:39:20,284
- Three?
- No.

1424
01:39:20,458 --> 01:39:21,891
Two?

1425
01:39:22,059 --> 01:39:23,287
No, no.

1426
01:39:23,461 --> 01:39:26,294
You've only delivered one lecture?

1427
01:39:26,998 --> 01:39:28,625
None, sir.

1428
01:39:28,799 --> 01:39:31,233
Don't tell me you haven't delivered
a single lecture?

1429
01:39:31,402 --> 01:39:33,996
Yes, sir, I've not delivered no lecture.

1430
01:39:34,171 --> 01:39:35,502
Any lecture.

1431
01:39:35,673 --> 01:39:37,937
Have you organized a League
for Democratic Action?

1432
01:39:38,109 --> 01:39:40,771
Yes, sir, I did that. I sure did.
I sure did that, sir.

1433
01:39:40,945 --> 01:39:43,937
How many lectures on democratic theory
did you give them?

1434
01:39:46,717 --> 01:39:48,981
- None, sir.
- You can't mean none.

1435
01:39:49,153 --> 01:39:52,611
- You must mean one or two.
- No, just none.

1436
01:39:52,790 --> 01:39:54,815
- I refuse to believe it.
- I'm very glad, sir.

1437
01:39:54,992 --> 01:39:57,790
- Sir, I must go.
- Where?

1438
01:39:57,962 --> 01:40:00,829
My seedlings are wilting.
I have to transplant them.

1439
01:40:00,998 --> 01:40:06,368
Captain, you'll pack your gear
and transplant yourself to your unit at once.

1440
01:40:06,537 --> 01:40:08,402
Yes, sir.

1441
01:40:09,106 --> 01:40:10,971
They'll die.

1442
01:40:11,575 --> 01:40:13,634
This is murder.

1443
01:40:16,814 --> 01:40:20,807
Please, take care of my beans.

1444
01:40:23,387 --> 01:40:26,948
Now, is the schoolhouse finished?

1445
01:40:27,258 --> 01:40:28,520
No, sir.

1446
01:40:28,692 --> 01:40:30,785
Why isn't it finished?

1447
01:40:31,062 --> 01:40:34,293
Well, we haven't started.

1448
01:40:34,465 --> 01:40:36,899
What did you do with the lumber I sent?

1449
01:40:37,134 --> 01:40:39,602
We built a teahouse.

1450
01:40:40,071 --> 01:40:42,596
I don't suppose
you have any aspirin here?

1451
01:40:44,408 --> 01:40:46,035
l... No, I don't think so.

1452
01:40:46,210 --> 01:40:47,802
What in the name of occupation...

1453
01:40:47,978 --> 01:40:50,071
...do you mean by saying
you built a teahouse?

1454
01:40:50,247 --> 01:40:54,775
Lotus Blossom, she had to have a place
to teach the League geisha lessons, sir.

1455
01:40:54,952 --> 01:40:58,388
- Fisby!
- Yes? Yes, sir? What?

1456
01:41:01,859 --> 01:41:03,656
How could you sink
to such depths, man?

1457
01:41:03,828 --> 01:41:07,889
Well, I was only giving in to
what the majority wanted, colonel.

1458
01:41:08,099 --> 01:41:11,762
I don't doubt that statement, not at all.

1459
01:41:11,936 --> 01:41:17,875
It's a sad thing it took a war to convince me
that most of the human race is degenerate.

1460
01:41:18,175 --> 01:41:20,439
I thank my stars I come from a country...

1461
01:41:20,611 --> 01:41:23,102
...where the air is clean,
where the wind is fresh...

1462
01:41:23,280 --> 01:41:24,713
Oh, for heaven's sakes, sir.

1463
01:41:24,882 --> 01:41:27,851
Nothing goes on in a teahouse
that your mother couldn't watch.

1464
01:41:28,018 --> 01:41:31,044
You be careful how you use
my mother's name, Fisby!

1465
01:41:31,222 --> 01:41:33,281
My mother, then, sir.

1466
01:41:33,457 --> 01:41:35,789
Sir, there's nothing immoral
about our teahouse.

1467
01:41:36,060 --> 01:41:39,655
Answer me this, what is bringing all that
occupation money to this village?

1468
01:41:43,234 --> 01:41:46,533
- Well, answer it.
- No, no, no. It's nothing, nothing.

1469
01:41:46,704 --> 01:41:49,195
- It might be for me. Answer it.
- It's not, you see...

1470
01:41:49,373 --> 01:41:52,740
- You see, this phone, it rings all day.
- Then I'll answer it.

1471
01:41:52,977 --> 01:41:54,740
Hello?

1472
01:41:56,313 --> 01:41:58,247
What do you want?

1473
01:41:58,916 --> 01:42:00,679
Who is this?

1474
01:42:01,385 --> 01:42:03,649
Commander Myers,
you must have a wrong connection.

1475
01:42:03,821 --> 01:42:06,221
This is not a brewery.

1476
01:42:07,491 --> 01:42:09,186
Yes.

1477
01:42:09,593 --> 01:42:11,220
Yes.

1478
01:42:12,396 --> 01:42:16,560
Yes. Oh, I see.

1479
01:42:16,734 --> 01:42:18,998
I see.

1480
01:42:21,305 --> 01:42:22,636
I see.

1481
01:42:26,710 --> 01:42:28,075
Well...

1482
01:42:31,682 --> 01:42:33,946
There was nothing else
that we could make...

1483
01:42:34,118 --> 01:42:36,780
...that anybody would want to buy.

1484
01:42:38,322 --> 01:42:40,017
Brandy.

1485
01:42:41,292 --> 01:42:43,852
This ends my Army career.

1486
01:42:44,495 --> 01:42:48,124
And I promised Mrs. Purdy
I'd come out a general.

1487
01:42:49,433 --> 01:42:53,267
You've broken
a fine woman's heart, Fisby.

1488
01:42:54,305 --> 01:42:56,865
I'm sorry. I'm very sorry.

1489
01:42:57,041 --> 01:42:59,976
You've sullied the reputation
of your nation and all the tears...

1490
01:43:00,144 --> 01:43:02,772
All right. Shall I kill myself?

1491
01:43:02,947 --> 01:43:05,177
Oh, don't minimize this.

1492
01:43:05,349 --> 01:43:08,477
You don't know the enemy's genius
for propaganda.

1493
01:43:08,886 --> 01:43:13,289
Well, what have you done with
all the money you've made so dishonestly?

1494
01:43:13,457 --> 01:43:15,652
I banked it in Seattle.

1495
01:43:16,894 --> 01:43:19,590
That's despicable.

1496
01:43:19,830 --> 01:43:23,266
Making a personal fortune off the labor
of these ignorant people.

1497
01:43:23,434 --> 01:43:26,926
I haven't touched a cent
of this money, colonel.

1498
01:43:27,104 --> 01:43:30,596
Now, it's banked in the name
of the Tobiki Cooperative Company.

1499
01:43:30,774 --> 01:43:34,904
See, everybody in the village,
they're all partners, don't you see?

1500
01:43:35,079 --> 01:43:36,546
You know, share and share alike.

1501
01:43:36,714 --> 01:43:38,978
That's communism!

1502
01:43:39,149 --> 01:43:40,844
It is?

1503
01:43:42,920 --> 01:43:45,821
I'll be lucky to get out
of this war a private.

1504
01:43:49,426 --> 01:43:50,893
- Captain Fisby...
- Yes, sir.

1505
01:43:51,061 --> 01:43:53,154
...you will consider yourself under arrest.

1506
01:43:53,330 --> 01:43:55,992
You'll proceed to HQ at once
to await court-martial.

1507
01:43:56,166 --> 01:43:59,932
I intend to wipe this stain
from our country's honor.

1508
01:44:00,104 --> 01:44:02,072
- Gregovich!
- You called, sir?

1509
01:44:02,239 --> 01:44:04,070
I did.

1510
01:44:06,343 --> 01:44:07,970
Yes, sir.

1511
01:44:09,546 --> 01:44:12,481
We have business to attend to here
before going to Awasi.

1512
01:44:12,650 --> 01:44:14,550
Yes, sir. I'm glad to hear it.

1513
01:44:14,718 --> 01:44:18,415
Captain, may I congratulate you
on what you've done for this village?

1514
01:44:18,589 --> 01:44:21,319
- It's a dream.
- Thank you, very much, sarg...

1515
01:44:21,492 --> 01:44:23,585
It's an alcoholic dream!

1516
01:44:23,761 --> 01:44:25,786
It's one vast distillery.

1517
01:44:25,963 --> 01:44:29,262
Take a detail and some axes
and smash every still in this village.

1518
01:44:29,433 --> 01:44:31,264
Destroy them?

1519
01:44:31,635 --> 01:44:33,330
Beyond repair.

1520
01:44:33,504 --> 01:44:36,064
Take another detail
and rip down that teahouse.

1521
01:44:36,240 --> 01:44:39,073
- But, colonel.
- Pile the lumber beside the road.

1522
01:44:39,243 --> 01:44:41,973
That's an order. Do you understand?

1523
01:44:43,113 --> 01:44:44,705
Yes, sir.

1524
01:45:04,268 --> 01:45:05,496
I know.

1525
01:46:34,992 --> 01:46:37,552
Hot water.

1526
01:47:21,138 --> 01:47:22,730
Boss. Sorry, boss.

1527
01:47:22,906 --> 01:47:24,430
Jeep all loaded now.

1528
01:47:26,577 --> 01:47:28,602
I'll be along in a minute, Sakini.

1529
01:47:29,213 --> 01:47:31,204
You going to take
Lotus Blossom with you?

1530
01:47:32,716 --> 01:47:34,581
Sakini.

1531
01:47:43,961 --> 01:47:49,627
Ask her for me if there's anything
that I can do for her before I go.

1532
01:47:49,800 --> 01:47:51,461
Ask her.

1533
01:48:01,578 --> 01:48:03,512
What did she say, Sakini?

1534
01:48:03,680 --> 01:48:06,148
She say she want to marry you, boss.

1535
01:48:07,384 --> 01:48:10,581
Now, why...?
Why would she want to marry me?

1536
01:48:12,289 --> 01:48:15,554
She say you nicest man
she ever seen, boss.

1537
01:48:15,993 --> 01:48:17,221
Oh, no, no, no.

1538
01:48:17,394 --> 01:48:20,386
No. You tell her for me that I'm clumsy.

1539
01:48:20,564 --> 01:48:22,691
I got...

1540
01:48:23,233 --> 01:48:26,259
I got a talent for destruction.

1541
01:48:26,436 --> 01:48:27,960
I'd only disillusion her...

1542
01:48:28,138 --> 01:48:31,665
...just the same way
I disillusioned all her people.

1543
01:48:39,216 --> 01:48:42,674
She say she like to go
to America, boss...

1544
01:48:42,853 --> 01:48:46,949
...where everyone happy, sit around
and sip tea while machine do work.

1545
01:48:47,357 --> 01:48:49,484
Tell her I'll never forget her.

1546
01:48:49,826 --> 01:48:52,351
I'll never forget this village...

1547
01:48:52,529 --> 01:48:55,930
...and on the other side of the world
in the autumn of my life...

1548
01:48:56,099 --> 01:48:59,000
...when an august moon
rises in the east...

1549
01:48:59,169 --> 01:49:01,933
...l'll remember what was beautiful...

1550
01:49:02,639 --> 01:49:06,006
...and what I was wise enough
to leave beautiful.

1551
01:49:30,934 --> 01:49:34,267
She say, boss, she never forget you.

1552
01:49:34,671 --> 01:49:39,301
She like you to know that she gonna
make up a long song-story about you...

1553
01:49:39,476 --> 01:49:41,774
...to sing in the teahouse.

1554
01:49:42,179 --> 01:49:45,774
And she say maybe in 100 years
from now...

1555
01:49:45,949 --> 01:49:48,918
...you gonna be famous
all over Okinawa.

1556
01:49:51,355 --> 01:49:54,222
I'd like that. I'd like that.

1557
01:50:16,513 --> 01:50:19,744
Oh, he sure want to push
her wheelbarrow for her, boss.

1558
01:50:22,619 --> 01:50:26,953
She say okay, but not to think
that she's his property.

1559
01:50:32,529 --> 01:50:35,430
He very happy fellow, boss.

1560
01:50:56,486 --> 01:51:00,115
She going now, boss,
but you still her boss...

1561
01:51:00,290 --> 01:51:04,351
...so she say she not go
till you drop fan from face.

1562
01:51:56,813 --> 01:52:00,408
I've written a full report of this whole affair
to your commanding officer.

1563
01:52:00,584 --> 01:52:02,575
I'm only glad you don't belong
to my outfit.

1564
01:52:02,753 --> 01:52:04,744
I won't tolerate rotten apples
in my barrel.

1565
01:52:06,723 --> 01:52:08,247
Hello.

1566
01:52:09,760 --> 01:52:11,284
Who?

1567
01:52:12,629 --> 01:52:14,153
What?

1568
01:52:15,165 --> 01:52:16,655
When?

1569
01:52:25,142 --> 01:52:27,975
Sit down, captain. Sit down. Sit down.

1570
01:52:28,879 --> 01:52:30,870
Make yourself comfortable.

1571
01:52:31,748 --> 01:52:33,875
Sit down. Give me your hat.

1572
01:52:34,050 --> 01:52:36,382
<i>Have some of these tsukemonos.</i>

1573
01:52:39,689 --> 01:52:42,886
Take your shoes off. I'll be right back.

1574
01:52:51,434 --> 01:52:54,870
- Going now, boss?
- Yeah, I guess so, Sakini.

1575
01:53:01,344 --> 01:53:03,608
Hey, boss, since you
not take Lotus Blossom...

1576
01:53:03,780 --> 01:53:06,214
...maybe you take me.

1577
01:53:06,850 --> 01:53:08,681
No, Sakini, no.

1578
01:53:08,852 --> 01:53:11,844
I work for you
for half price, boss.

1579
01:53:12,289 --> 01:53:16,157
Major McEvoy is coming down here
to take charge...

1580
01:53:17,327 --> 01:53:20,091
...and, well, he's going to
need your help, you know.

1581
01:53:20,263 --> 01:53:23,460
You very hard man
to bargain with, boss.

1582
01:53:23,633 --> 01:53:26,625
Okay, you want,
I work just for rice ration.

1583
01:53:28,004 --> 01:53:29,232
No.

1584
01:53:30,040 --> 01:53:32,406
You mean you gonna make me
work for nothing, boss?

1585
01:53:33,710 --> 01:53:37,476
I mean, yes, you're not going to
work for me at all, Sakini.

1586
01:53:37,647 --> 01:53:41,447
- No, you belong here.
- Okay, boss.

1587
01:53:46,356 --> 01:53:50,452
Boss, you know what I think gonna happen
when American leave Okinawa?

1588
01:53:50,627 --> 01:53:51,958
No, what?

1589
01:53:52,128 --> 01:53:54,119
I think we gonna have to use...

1590
01:53:54,297 --> 01:53:58,233
...a pentagon-shaped schoolhouse
for teahouse.

1591
01:54:03,740 --> 01:54:05,901
So long, Sakini.

1592
01:54:06,877 --> 01:54:08,572
You're a rare rascal.

1593
01:54:09,179 --> 01:54:11,306
So long, boss.

1594
01:54:12,449 --> 01:54:14,076
Say, you know, I'm gonna miss you.

1595
01:54:16,720 --> 01:54:19,689
- Hey, boss.
- Yes?

1596
01:54:20,223 --> 01:54:23,158
You not failure.

1597
01:54:27,397 --> 01:54:29,831
I'll tell you something, Sakini.

1598
01:54:30,066 --> 01:54:34,560
You know, I used to worry a lot
about not being a big success.

1599
01:54:34,938 --> 01:54:38,066
I think I felt an awful lot
like you people felt...

1600
01:54:38,241 --> 01:54:40,368
...always being conquered.

1601
01:54:40,777 --> 01:54:43,974
Well, you know,
now I'm not sure who's the conquered...

1602
01:54:45,115 --> 01:54:47,083
...and who's the conqueror.

1603
01:54:47,684 --> 01:54:52,815
I've learned in Tobiki,
the wisdom of gracious acceptance.

1604
01:54:53,056 --> 01:54:55,820
See, I don't want to be a world leader.

1605
01:54:56,226 --> 01:54:59,593
I've made peace with myself
somewhere between my ambitions...

1606
01:54:59,763 --> 01:55:01,355
...and my limitations.

1607
01:55:02,098 --> 01:55:04,328
That's good, boss.

1608
01:55:06,436 --> 01:55:09,428
Well, it's a step backward
in the right direction.

1609
01:55:13,410 --> 01:55:14,809
Take care.

1610
01:55:15,345 --> 01:55:17,540
Socks up, boss.

1611
01:55:27,290 --> 01:55:28,917
Sakini! Sakini!

1612
01:55:29,426 --> 01:55:31,724
Sakini. Sakini.

1613
01:55:31,895 --> 01:55:33,123
Where's Captain Fisby?

1614
01:55:33,863 --> 01:55:35,296
Right over here, boss.
This way.

1615
01:55:35,465 --> 01:55:37,626
- Fisby.
- No, no, over here.

1616
01:55:37,801 --> 01:55:41,703
Fisby. Fisby.
Fisby, come back here at once.

1617
01:55:41,871 --> 01:55:43,532
I'm not in shape.
Too much paperwork.

1618
01:55:43,707 --> 01:55:45,834
- You called, sir?
- I've been looking for you.

1619
01:55:46,009 --> 01:55:49,172
You can't leave. You've got to stay here.
You've got to help me.

1620
01:55:49,346 --> 01:55:50,813
I don't understand, colonel.

1621
01:55:50,981 --> 01:55:53,313
We've got to pull this village
back together again.

1622
01:55:53,483 --> 01:55:55,508
The lid has blown off of everything.

1623
01:55:55,685 --> 01:55:57,915
- Where's Gregovich?
- Well, he... He's out there.

1624
01:55:58,088 --> 01:56:00,488
- They're breaking up the rest of the stills.
- Oh, no.

1625
01:56:00,657 --> 01:56:03,455
- Why? What's the matter?
- I radioed the report to Washington.

1626
01:56:03,626 --> 01:56:05,355
Some fool senator misunderstood.

1627
01:56:05,528 --> 01:56:08,656
He's using this village as an example
of American get-up-and-go...

1628
01:56:08,832 --> 01:56:11,494
...in the recovery program.
We're all over the newspapers.

1629
01:56:11,668 --> 01:56:14,193
- That's wonderful, colonel.
- It's not wonderful.

1630
01:56:14,371 --> 01:56:17,431
A congressional committee
is flying over here to study our methods.

1631
01:56:17,607 --> 01:56:20,804
They're bringing photographers
for a magazine spread. Tonight, Fisby.

1632
01:56:20,977 --> 01:56:23,445
- Oh, that's bad, that's bad.
- Gregovich!

1633
01:56:23,613 --> 01:56:26,377
Maybe there's a way we could stall them.
Maybe we could...

1634
01:56:26,549 --> 01:56:28,574
Maybe we could
quarantine the place.

1635
01:56:28,752 --> 01:56:32,313
You can't quarantine a congressman.
They've got immunity or something.

1636
01:56:32,555 --> 01:56:34,386
- Fisby?
- Yeah.

1637
01:56:34,557 --> 01:56:35,683
- Help me.
- Yes, sir.

1638
01:56:35,859 --> 01:56:38,123
I don't ask it for my sake.

1639
01:56:39,496 --> 01:56:41,896
I ask it for Mrs. Purdy.

1640
01:56:43,833 --> 01:56:46,131
I could be a brigadier yet.

1641
01:56:47,270 --> 01:56:48,669
Gregovich?

1642
01:56:58,248 --> 01:57:01,274
Gregovich! Gregovich.

1643
01:57:03,019 --> 01:57:04,748
- Gregovich.
- Did you call, sir?

1644
01:57:04,921 --> 01:57:06,946
Come here, come here, Gregovich.

1645
01:57:07,724 --> 01:57:09,954
You haven't destroyed all the stills,
have you?

1646
01:57:10,126 --> 01:57:11,991
No. No, of course you haven't.

1647
01:57:12,162 --> 01:57:14,323
Oh, yes, I have.

1648
01:57:14,731 --> 01:57:17,291
I carried orders out to the letter.

1649
01:57:17,467 --> 01:57:20,925
Why can't somebody
disobey orders once in a while?

1650
01:57:21,104 --> 01:57:24,130
What's happened to
the American spirit of rebellion?

1651
01:57:29,412 --> 01:57:32,176
- Sunstroke?
- Potato brandy, sir.

1652
01:57:34,017 --> 01:57:35,644
Sergeant, wake up.

1653
01:57:36,086 --> 01:57:37,576
Do you hear me? That's an order.

1654
01:57:37,754 --> 01:57:40,882
- Colonel, I'm afraid he's passed out.
- It's desertion.

1655
01:57:41,057 --> 01:57:43,184
I need every man.
Gregovich, get to your feet.

1656
01:57:43,359 --> 01:57:45,987
Come on, sergeant.
Come on, sergeant.

1657
01:57:46,162 --> 01:57:47,356
Gregovich.

1658
01:57:47,530 --> 01:57:50,397
- I wanna ask you some questions.
- Sorry, sir.

1659
01:57:50,567 --> 01:57:53,559
- Stop weaving.
- You're weaving, sir.

1660
01:57:53,736 --> 01:57:55,761
I'm standing perfectly still.

1661
01:57:55,939 --> 01:57:57,804
You smell like a brewery.

1662
01:57:57,974 --> 01:58:00,374
Well, I fell in a vat.

1663
01:58:00,543 --> 01:58:02,977
- You got drunk?
- No, sir.

1664
01:58:03,146 --> 01:58:04,909
I fell in a vat.

1665
01:58:05,081 --> 01:58:09,245
Naturally, I had to open my mouth
to yell for help.

1666
01:58:09,519 --> 01:58:13,319
- Go to the office and sober up at once.
- Yes, sir.

1667
01:58:15,291 --> 01:58:18,089
Oh, sergeant. Sergeant.

1668
01:58:18,261 --> 01:58:19,819
- Fisby.
- Yes, sir?

1669
01:58:19,996 --> 01:58:22,931
- I think I'm going to need you. Stand by.
- Yes, sir. Yes, sir.

1670
01:58:25,802 --> 01:58:27,360
No.

1671
01:58:38,348 --> 01:58:41,181
I'm a sinking ship...

1672
01:58:42,418 --> 01:58:45,387
...scuttled by my own men.

1673
01:58:46,122 --> 01:58:47,419
I know.

1674
01:58:47,824 --> 01:58:50,486
- Colonel Purdy.
- Don't bother me.

1675
01:58:50,660 --> 01:58:52,355
Stills not all destroyed.

1676
01:58:52,529 --> 01:58:54,588
I haven't got time.

1677
01:58:55,999 --> 01:58:57,523
What did you say?

1678
01:58:57,700 --> 01:58:59,292
We not born yesterday.

1679
01:58:59,469 --> 01:59:02,768
We get the sergeant drunk.
Give him water barrel to break.

1680
01:59:02,939 --> 01:59:04,497
Sakini...

1681
01:59:06,442 --> 01:59:07,932
...my friend.

1682
01:59:08,111 --> 01:59:10,204
You're not saying this
to make me feel better?

1683
01:59:10,380 --> 01:59:13,247
No. Stills as good as ever, boss.

1684
01:59:13,416 --> 01:59:15,281
Production not cease yet.

1685
01:59:15,451 --> 01:59:17,476
Sakini, you really are a rascal.

1686
01:59:17,654 --> 01:59:20,589
No, he's really an American.

1687
01:59:20,757 --> 01:59:22,315
He's got get-up-and-go.

1688
01:59:22,492 --> 01:59:25,791
Sakini, if you could get
the people in the village to work together...

1689
01:59:25,962 --> 01:59:28,897
...how long do you think it'd take them
to rebuild the teahouse?

1690
01:59:29,065 --> 01:59:31,761
We not destroy, boss.
We just take away and hide.

1691
01:59:31,935 --> 01:59:33,766
Look, come here.

1692
01:59:38,408 --> 01:59:42,640
Now we going to show you
Okinawan get-up-and-go.

1693
02:00:36,466 --> 02:00:38,366
Be right back.

1694
02:01:29,552 --> 02:01:33,420
It's a land of mystery of the Orient.

1695
02:01:33,589 --> 02:01:36,251
It's... It's beautiful.

1696
02:01:36,426 --> 02:01:37,984
Simply beautiful.

1697
02:01:38,161 --> 02:01:39,492
There's only one thing wrong.

1698
02:01:39,662 --> 02:01:43,223
It needs a sign to tell people what it is.

1699
02:01:43,399 --> 02:01:47,995
And we ought to put another sign up over
there naming this Grace Purdy Avenue...

1700
02:01:48,171 --> 02:01:49,570
...and another sign...

1701
02:01:49,739 --> 02:01:52,333
Sir, how about a nice cup of tea?

1702
02:01:52,675 --> 02:01:55,576
- All right? Come on, colonel.
- All right.

1703
02:01:56,979 --> 02:02:00,710
- Twenty Star for the colonel, Sakini.
- Okay, boss.

1704
02:02:12,195 --> 02:02:14,425
Little story now concluded...

1705
02:02:14,597 --> 02:02:17,532
...but history of world unfinished.

1706
02:02:17,700 --> 02:02:22,603
Lovely ladies, kind gentlemen,
go home to ponder.

1707
02:02:22,772 --> 02:02:26,765
What was true at beginning
remains true.

1708
02:02:26,943 --> 02:02:31,539
Pain make man think,
thought make man wise...

1709
02:02:31,714 --> 02:02:34,808
...and wisdom make life endurable.

1710
02:02:35,885 --> 02:02:40,879
So may august moon
bring gentle sleep.

1711
02:02:41,924 --> 02:02:43,414
Sayonara.